{"log_type": "agent_output", "timestamp_iso": "2026-03-20T09:45:11", "timestamp_unix": 1774017911, "data": {"type": "result", "subtype": "success", "is_error": false, "duration_ms": 460777, "duration_api_ms": 471488, "num_turns": 28, "result": "[THOUGHT]\nNow I have the full picture. In `xmlParseCharEncoding` (encoding.c:1153), `char upper[500]` is declared but **not zero-initialized**. The loop fills `upper[0..strlen(name)]` (inclusive of null), but leaves `upper[strlen(name)+1 .. 499]` as uninitialized stack bytes.\n\nAt line 1180: `strcmp(upper, \"UTF-16\")` \u2014 MSan's implementation of `strcmp` reads all 7 bytes of the \"UTF-16\\0\" region from `upper`. If `name` has \u22645 characters (e.g., \"utf-8\"), then `upper[6]` is uninitialized \u2192 MSan fires at offset 6 inside a 7-byte region.\n\nRoot cause: `upper` is not zero-initialized, so any `strcmp` against a string literal longer than the input leaves the tail bytes as uninitialized. The minimal fix is `char upper[500] = {0};` \u2014 zero-initializing at declaration.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"status\": \"PATCH_READY\",\n  \"patches\": [\n    {\n      \"file\": \"encoding.c\",\n      \"diff\": \"--- a/encoding.c\\n+++ b/encoding.c\\n@@ -1150,7 +1150,7 @@\\n xmlParseCharEncoding(const char* name)\\n {\\n     const char *alias;\\n-    char upper[500];\\n+    char upper[500] = {0};\\n     int i;\\n \\n     if (name == NULL)\\n\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```", "stop_reason": null, "session_id": "354b8151-95e2-442f-9f36-bd43a04b3f0a", "total_cost_usd": 1.2194010000000002, "usage": {"input_tokens": 1057, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 27633, "cache_read_input_tokens": 783211, "output_tokens": 24094, "server_tool_use": {"web_search_requests": 0, "web_fetch_requests": 0}, "service_tier": "standard", "cache_creation": {"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens": 27633, "ephemeral_5m_input_tokens": 0}, "inference_geo": "", "iterations": [], "speed": "standard"}, "modelUsage": {"claude-sonnet-4-6": {"inputTokens": 1065, "outputTokens": 24654, "cac